
claim_dictionary 
industry – e.g., Healthcare, Technology
•sub_industry – e.g., Life Sciences Tools & Diagnostics, Software - B2B SaaS
•metric_key – name (stable key)
•critical – Y/N (missing this should hurt score more)
•keyword_triggers – phrases that indicate the metric is being discussed
•allowed_units – (pct, bps, usd_bn, usd_mn, x, count, months)
•required_periods – (FY, LTM, Q, Y)
•value_required – Y/N (some metrics can be mentioned qualitatively; most should be Y)
{"k":"ebitda_margin", "u":["pct","bps"], "kw":["EBITDA margin","operating margin"]}

Section_topic_dictionary
Purpose: tells the system what topics must be covered for each section (even if no numbers). This powers “coverage scoring”.
•section_type – one of: company_overview,operating_performance, industry_trends, key_risks, key_mitigants
•industry
•sub_industry
•topic_key – canonical coverage bucket name
•required – Y/N (must hit or fail/cap)
•keywords –
•min_hits – usually 1 (or more if you want stronger evidence)
{"t":"regulatory_quality", "kw":["FDA","recall","compliance"]}

Entity_aliases
•	industry
•	sub_industry
•	canon_entity – the canonical name your system will use (stable key)

•	entity_type – e.g., ORG, SEGMENT, PRODUCT, METRIC, DOC, GEO
•	alias – one alias per row
